<TITLE> Nigerian oil state governor's wife arrested in UK </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Nov 2 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British police have arrested a Nigerian woman in connection with a money-laundering investigation targeting her husband, the former governor of one of Nigeria's richest oil states, police said on Friday. James Ibori, who governed Delta State for eight years during which its revenues soared thanks to high oil prices, has already had assets worth $35 million frozen by a British court while police investigate him under the Proceeds of Crime Act. Ibori was one of the main campaign sponsors of President Umaru Yar'Adua, who took office on May 29. His case is seen as a test of the government's seriousness about tackling graft in a country where having friends in high places has traditionally been a reliable shield from the law. "A 39-year-old woman was arrested at Heathrow (airport) yesterday in connection with an ongoing money laundering inquiry, and is in custody at a West London police station," said a spokeswoman for London's Metropolitan Police. British police do not give the names of suspects until they are formally charged. The spokeswoman was asked whether Ibori's wife, Theresa, had been detained. As a state governor, Ibori had immunity from prosecution in Nigeria until his tenure ended on May 29. Since then, British and Nigerian investigators have been looking into his case. Ibori has obtained a pre-emptive court injunction stopping Nigeria's anti-corruption police, the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission, from arresting him. The commission is challenging that order. The situation is further complicated by a power struggle within the Nigerian authorities. The anti-corruption commission appears keen to prosecute Ibori, but Nigerian Attorney General Michael Aondoakaa has repeatedly criticised the commission and tried to bring it under his authority. Nigeria's president has said no politician would be protected from the law and that he authorised a visit to Nigeria by British police investigating Ibori. But anti-corruption